International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 15 March 2007
From: Lorenzo Capucci <lcapucci@bs.izs.it> & Antonio Lavazza
<alavazza@bs.izs.it>

It would be very interesting to verify the calicivirus -- viral
rabbit hemorrhagic disease (RHD) -- hypothesis. In fact, we should
consider that, until now, only the European rabbit (_Oryctolagus
cuniculus_), wild or domestic, has been shown to be fully susceptible
to the RHD virus, and all attempts to reproduce the disease in other
lagomorph species (_Lepus_ spp. and _Sylvilagus_ spp.) have failed.
To our knowledge the known pathogenic caliciviruses of the
_Lagovirus_ genus (RHDV [Rabbit haemorrhagic disease virus] and EBHSV
[European brown hare syndrome virus]) are strictly species-specific.
For this reason, we would be very pleased to examine the sample [from
_Brachylagus idahoensis_] and, in case of positive results for RHDV,
to perform a full antigenic and genomic characterization of the strain.
--
Lorenzo Capucci
<lcapucci@bs.izs.it>
Antonio Lavazza
<alavazza@bs.izs.it>
OIE Reference Laboratory for Haemorrhagic Diseases of Lagomorphs
Istituto Zooprofilattico Sperimentale della Lombardia e dell'Emilia
Romagna (IZSLER)
Via Bianchi 7/9
25124 Brescia (Italy)
