[2]
Date: Wed 14 Mar 2007
From: Kristin Mansfield <mansfkgm@DFW.WA.GOV>

Between 6 Feb and 14 Mar 2007, 10 of 20 pygmy rabbits housed at
Northwest Trek Wildlife Park have died. There does not appear to be
an age or sex predilection. The only antemortem clinical sign noted
has been soft stools within 12 hours of death in about half of the
deceased rabbits.
The rabbits are part of a captive breeding program designed to
produce animals in order to re-establish this endangered species in
the wild in the state of Washington.
Acute erosive ileotyphlitis [inflammation of the ileum and caecum]
and colitis are the most significant pathologic findings in 4 of the
5 rabbits for which histology has been completed.
From the pathology reports: "The changes in the alimentary tract are
acute and likely to be the cause of death. These changes most closely
resemble bacterial infection, as might occur with colibacillosis or
clostridial enterotoxemia, but _Lawsonia_, coronavirus, or rotavirus
may also be contributing." Bacterial cultures and electron microscopy
for viruses are pending.
Infection control measures, including isolating rabbits in individual
crates, have been implemented. All surviving rabbits are receiving
supportive care and empirical treatment as needed.
Rabbits at the other 2 captive breeding facilities -- Washington
State University (WSU) in Pullman, WA, and the Oregon Zoo in
Portland, OR -- are currently unaffected; 20 captive-bred pygmy
rabbits from these 2 institutions were released into a former pygmy
rabbit range yesterday [13 Mar 2007], marking the 1st time in 5 years
that they have occurred in the wild in Washington [state].
Approximately 100 pygmy rabbits remain in captivity at WSU and the Oregon Zoo.
--
Kristin Mansfield DVM, MPVM
Wildlife Veterinarian
Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife
2315 North Discovery Place
Spokane Valley, WA 99216-1566
Office (509) 892-1001 ext. 326
Fax (509) 921-2440
Mobile (509) 998-2023
<mansfkgm@DFW.WA.GOV>
[The information presented by Lorenzo Capucci and Antonio Lavazza of
OIE (World Animal Health Organization) is most interesting, but from
the initial pathology results, it appears that RHD can be ruled out.
We are thankful to Lorenzo Capucci, Antonio Lavazza, and Dr.
Mansfield for the informative update. - Mod.TG]
